t our lifetimes American society has been age-conscious. But this has not always been the case. Until the mid-nineteenth century, Americans showed little concern with age. The one-room schoolhouse was filled with students of varied ages, and children worked alongside adults. [This is] a lively picture of the development of age consciousness in urban middle-class culture." --Robert H. Binstock, The New York Times Book Review "A fresh perspective on a century of social and cultural development."--Michael R. Dahlin, American Historical Review  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aCalahan, Daniel.  aDanzinger, Sheldon.  aEddy, Daniel.  aEliot, Charles W.  aForty Plus clubs.  aFreud, Sigmund.  aGerontological Society.  aHart, William Bruce.  aKett, Joseph.  aLee, Agnes.  aLionberger, Isaac.  aMedicare.  aMorris, Desmond.  aNational Council of Senior Citizens.  aNewcomb, Harvey.  aOlder Americans Act of 1965.  aPuritans.  aQuetelet, Adolphe.  aShakespeare, William.  aSunday schools.  aTitcomb, Timothy.  aTucker, Sophie.  aVietnam War.  aWillard, Frances.  aZnaniecki, Florian.  aadvice literature.  aageism.  aautograph books.  ababy boom.  abirthrates.  abureaucratization.  achild development.  acolleges and universities.  acommercialized leisure.  adiscrimination, age.  agames and play.  ainfant schools.  ajukeboxes.  ajuvenile courts.  amiddle age.  apediatrics.  apeer groups.  areligion.  aretirement communities.  arural communities.  asocial security.  atelevision.  avaudeville.  avoting age.  awork and workplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691221267zCo-acces